chive.org/web/20190412200124/https://torontosun.com/opinion/columnists/lilley-ford-plan-takes-city-forward |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"newsontario\">{{cite news |url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2019/04/premier-ford-unveils-transportation-vision.html |title=Premier Ford Unveils Transportation Vision: Ontario Announces $28.5{{nbsp}}Billion to Get Ontario Moving |publisher=Government of Ontario |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 10, 2019 |quote=Joined by Jeff Yurek, Minister of Transportation, and Monte McNaughton, Minister of Infrastructure, Ford announced a $28.5{{nbsp}}billion expansion to Ontario's transit network. This is the most money ever invested to get shovels in the ground and get new subways built. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410213847/https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2019/04/premier-ford-unveils-transportation-vision.html |archive-date=April 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"budgetontario-sec1\">{{cite web |url=http://budget.ontario.ca/2019/chapter-1b.html#s-1 |publisher=Government of Ontario |title=The New \"Ontario Line\" \u2013 Better, Faster, Smarter |accessdate=May 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416225924/http://budget.ontario.ca/2019/chapter-1b.html#s-1 |archive-date=April 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"budgetontario\">{{cite news |url=http://budget.ontario.ca/2019/chapter-1b.html |title=Chapter 1, Section B: Putting People First |work=[[Government of Ontario]] |date=April 11, 2019 |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412001029/http://budget.ontario.ca/2019/chapter-1b.html |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"star-keenan\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2019/04/10/doug-fords-transit-plan-has-good-elements-but-ford-himself-is-cause-for-skepticism.html |title=Doug Ford's transit plan has good elements. But Ford himself is cause for skepticism |work=[[Toronto Star]] |first=Edward |last=Keenan |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |quote=Ford's relief line route \u2013 rebranded the \"Ontario Line\" here \u2013 is a significant improvement over the first-phase plan from Pape to Osgoode that the city has developed. While the western terminus at Ontario Place will do nothing to quell speculation he has plans to build a casino on the park site, stops in the west end in Liberty Village will be useful, and the Ontario Place/exhibition site has long suffered from less than ideal transit access. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505145358/https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2019/04/10/doug-fords-transit-plan-has-good-elements-but-ford-himself-is-cause-for-skepticism.html |archive-date=May 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cressy-ed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9278121-ford-transit-plan-like-groundhog-day-for-waterfront-coun-joe-cressy/ |title=Ford transit plan like 'Groundhog Day' for waterfront: Coun. Joe Cressy: Ontario Place must remain public, says Waterfront for All coalition member |work=Toronto.com |first=Rahul |last=Gupta |date=April 11, 2019 |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |quote=Ontario Place has long been of interest to the premier dating back to his days as a Toronto city councillor. After his election win last year, Ford promised the tourist attraction will be revitalized, and his government refused to rule out a casino. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509063616/https://www.toronto.com/news-story/9278121-ford-transit-plan-like-groundhog-day-for-waterfront-coun-joe-cressy/ |archive-date=May 9, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"casinoscanada\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bestcasinoscanada.com/what-are-the-odds-of-casino-venue-operation-at-ontario-place/ |title=What Are The Odds Of Casino Venue Operation At Ontario Place? |work=Casinos Canada |accessdate=May 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504135152/https://www.bestcasinoscanada.com/what-are-the-odds-of-casino-venue-operation-at-ontario-place/ |archive-date=May 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"star-jacksonkelso\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/04/10/how-doug-fords-285-billion-transit-overhaul-compares-with-torontos-existing-plans.html |title=How Doug Ford's $28.5-billion transit overhaul compares with Toronto's existing plans |work=[[Toronto Star]] |first1=Rhianna |last1=Jackson-Kelso |first2=Emerald |last2=Bensadoun |date=April 10, 2019 |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |quote=Under the city's plan, the downtown relief line would run 7.4 kilometres connecting Queen and Osgoode stations to Pape station. The latest estimates had put the cost of the line at $7.2{{nbsp}}billion. The project had a tentative completion date of 2029 following a recently approved plan to spend $325{{nbsp}}million over two years finish more quickly. The environmental assessment for the city's version of the project, one of the final steps before the construction phase, was completed last October. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411040213/https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/04/10/how-doug-fords-285-billion-transit-overhaul-compares-with-torontos-existing-plans.html |archive-date=April 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TheStar2019-07-22\">{{cite news |url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-line-deviates-from-relief-line-more-than-previously-thought-report-1.4519754 |title=Ontario Line deviates from relief line more than previously thought: report |work=CTV News |first=Chris |last=Fox |date=July 23, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite report |year=2019 |url=https://metrolinx.files.wordpress.com/2019/07/click-here-to-view-the-ontario-line-initial-business-case.pdf |type=pdf |title=Ontario Line: Initial Business Case: July 2019 |publisher=Metrolinx |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}\n\n{{portalbar|Ontario|Trains}}\n{{TTC}}\n\n[[Category:Proposed Toronto rapid transit projects]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Proposed rapid transit line in Toronto}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Ontario Line\n|color       = \n|image       = \n|image_width = \n|caption     = \n|type        = [[Light metro]]\n|system      = [[Toronto subway]]\n|status      = Proposed\n|locale      = [[Toronto]], Ontario\n|start       = {{ttcs|Science Centre}}, {{GOs|Exhibition}}\n|end         = \n|stations    = 15\n|routes      =\n|daily_ridership = \n|owner       = [[Metrolinx]] \n|operator    = \n|character   = \n|stock       = \n|linelength_km = 15.5\n|tracklength =\n|tracks      = \n|gauge       = \n|electrification = \n|speed       =\n|elevation   =\n|website     = \n|map         = {{Ontario Line}}\n|map_state   = \n}}\nThe '''Ontario Line''' is a proposed [[rapid transit]] line in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada. Its northern terminus would be at [[Eglinton Avenue]] and [[Don Mills Road]], at [[Science Centre station]], where it would connect with [[Line 5 Eglinton]]. Its southern terminus would be at the existing [[Exhibition GO Station]] on the [[Lakeshore West line]]. The Ontario Line was announced by the [[Government of Ontario]] on April 10, 2019.<ref name=\"Cbc2019-04-10\" /><ref name=\"newsontario\" /> The Ontario government estimates the cost at {{CAD|10.9{{nbsp}}billion|link=yes}} for this {{convert|15.5|km|mi|adj=on}} line and hopes to complete the project by 2027.<ref name=\"Cbc2019-04-10\" />\n\n==Project history==\n[[File:Bloor-Yonge_service_disruption_March_2015.jpg|thumb|left|Bloor\u2013Yonge station during a service disruption on Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]]\n{{see also|Relief Line (Toronto)#Ontario Line}}\nThe [[Municipal government of Toronto|City of Toronto]] had been developing a rapid transit line, known as the \"[[Relief Line (Toronto)|Relief Line South]]\",{{efn|The \"relief\" would be to overcrowding at [[Bloor\u2013Yonge station]] and the Yonge Street section of Line 1.}} between [[Pape station]] on [[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth]] and [[Osgoode station]] on [[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]]. In the early months of 2019, the Ontario government announced its intentions to take over subway construction in Toronto. In a surprise announcement in April 2019, the Ontario government announced the Ontario Line, which at that time appeared to incorporate much of the routing and many of the station locations of the Relief Line.<ref name=\"budgetontario-sec1\" /> Unlike the City design, the Ontario Line would be a \"standalone\" line, one that would use lighter rolling stock and shorter trainsets than the [[Toronto Transit Commission]]'s [[Toronto subway|existing subway lines]].<ref name=\"budgetontario\" /> Members of Toronto City Council expressed their concerns that the new line would set back the delivery of rapid transit and potentially waste money the City of Toronto had already spent on the Relief Line's design.\n\nMetrolinx prepared the plan for the Ontario Line in just three months based on a proposal by transit consultant [[Michael Schabas]]. Metrolinx hired Schabas in December 2018 to lead a team to transform the Relief Line plans into the Ontario Line. Schabas was a proponent of using lighter metro vehicles such as those used for the London's [[Docklands Light Railway]], such vehicles being suitable for steeper grades and elevated structures. A draft plan was ready by January 31, 2019. Doug Ford approved the plan after a February 26 presentation. Metrolinx kept the project a secret until the government chose to announce it on April 10.<ref name=\"TheStar-2020-02-15\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2020/02/15/how-fords-ontario-line-plan-came-together-in-just-three-months-with-secrecy-a-shifting-route-and-a-consultant.html |title=How Ford\u2019s Ontario Line plan came together in just three months \u2014 with secrecy, a shifting route and a consultant |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |first=Ben |last=Spurr |date={{date|2020-02-15|mdy}} |accessdate={{date|2020-02-15|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\nAs initially announced in April 2019, the route of the Ontario Line seemed to follow much of the route of the Relief Line, beginning at [[Exhibition Place]], travelling northeast to King and Bathurst Streets, then northeast to Spadina Avenue and Queen Street. It then proceeded eastward through downtown along Queen Street before turning southeast in the area of Parliament Street south to Eastern Avenue. The line had one station on King and Sumach, then made an east\u2013west crossing of the [[Don River (Ontario)|Don River]] to a station at Broadview and Eastern Avenue. The line proceeded northeast to Pape Avenue and [[Danforth Avenue]] and continued north along Pape, making a north\u2013south crossing of the Don River to the Thorncliffe Park neighbourhood. The line continued northeast along Don Mills Road to terminate at Don Mills Road and Eglinton Avenue.<ref name=\"TheStar2019-04-11\" />\n\nThe announcement that the line would extend to a new station at Ontario Place stirred controversy, as Ontario Premier [[Doug Ford]] had spoken of transforming Ontario Place, previously a family-oriented venue, into an adult-oriented [[casino]] complex, and some suspected that the plan to have the transit line extend to Ontario Place was aimed at [[Gambling tourism|visiting gamblers]]<!--Don't bypass redirect per [[WP:NOTBROKEN]]-->, not the citizens of Ontario.<ref name=\"TheStar2019-04-12a\" /><ref name=\"star-keenan\" /><ref name=\"theglobeandmail2019-04-10\" /><ref name=\"cressy-ed\" /><ref name=\"casinoscanada\" /> Ford has denied that the extension is related to any casino plans.<ref name=\"sun201904\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that no previous plan had ever considered making Ontario Place a rapid transit destination and that the announcement surprised everyone, including [[Mayor of Toronto]] [[John Tory]].<ref name=\"theglobeandmail2019-04-10\" />\n\nIn July 2019, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' obtained and reported on confidential documents from [[Metrolinx]]. They showed that the proposed route would be markedly different from that of the Relief Line South and involve significant lengths of at-grade or elevated track. The Ontario Place station was eliminated with an Exhibition station added near the [[Exhibition GO Station]]. The section between Queen/Sherbourne and Gerrard stations would come to the surface and mostly follow a railway right-of-way instead of being tunnelled. The new route would substitute a [[Corktown, Toronto|Corktown]] station about {{Convert|500|m||abbr=}} west of the proposed location for Sumach station on the Relief Line. The Ontario Line would share less than half the planned route of the Relief Line between Osgoode and Pape stations.<ref name=\"TheStar2019-07-22\" />\n\nIn October 2019, Mayor John Tory and Premier Doug Ford reached a tentative deal in which the city would endorse the line and the [[Toronto subway|TTC's subway network]] would not be taken over by the [[Government of Ontario|provincial government]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spurr |first1=Ben |title=Mayor John Tory throws support behind Ontario Line as province drops subway upload |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/10/16/mayor-john-tory-throws-support-behind-ontario-line-in-deal-with-province-that-would-avoid-subway-upload.html |accessdate=October 17, 2019 |work=Toronto Star |publisher=Torstar |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref> The deal was later approved by Toronto City Council in a 22\u20133 decision.<ref>{{cite news |last=Freeman |first=Joshua |title=Council votes to approve transit expansion deal with the province |url=https://www.cp24.com/news/council-votes-to-approve-transit-expansion-deal-with-the-province-1.4661247 |work=CP24 |publisher=Bell Media |accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Concerns==\nAfter a draft of the Ontario Line's business case was disclosed in July 2019, a number of concerns were raised by transit experts:\n* Doubts were expressed that the line could be completed within budget and by 2027. Metrolinx plans to start the procurement process in 2020 to allow bidding companies to comment on the feasibility of the 2027 completion date.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\"/>\n* It may be challenging to fit the Ontario Line along GO Transit's [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East corridor]]. The Ontario Line would need to be added to three existing overpasses.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\"/> If the Ontario Line requires widening of the Lakeshore East embankment, property acquisitions may be required including nearby houses, businesses and community facilities.<ref name=\"TO-2019-10-15-A4\"><!--\"widening of the Lakeshore East GO rail corridor\"-->{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2019/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-138946.pdf |title=Attachment 4 \u2013 Assessment of Ontario Line |website=toronto.ca |publisher=[[Municipal government of Toronto|City of Toronto]] |date=2019-10-15 |accessdate=2019-10-29 }}</ref><ref name=\"TO-2019-10-15\">{{cite web |url=https://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2019/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-138688.pdf |title=Toronto-Ontario Transit Update |website=toronto.ca |publisher=[[Municipal government of Toronto|City of Toronto]] |date=2019-10-15 |accessdate=2019-10-29 }}</ref>\n* Flood mitigation projects and reconstruction of the Gardiner Expressway at Lower Don River may impede Ontario Line construction.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\"/>\n* There are doubts that passengers can alight and board smaller Ontario Line trains quickly enough to achieve the projected 90-second train frequency. Metrolinx insists the frequency can be met by reducing station dwell times.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\"/>  \n* There is a concern that winter conditions may adversely affect train operations on an elevated track like [[Line 3 Scarborough]], which also uses light metro technology.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\"/>\n* The elevated structures may have a greater environmental impact with respect to noise, vibration and visual presence than with an underground right-of-way. Metrolinx proposes using mitigation strategies involving \"systems, maintenance and track design\" to reduce noise and vibration, and new community spaces and parks \"to offset (the) visual impact and footprint of the elevated structure\".<ref name=\"Metrolinx-2019-07\">{{cite web |url=https://metrolinx.files.wordpress.com/2019/07/click-here-to-view-the-ontario-line-initial-business-case.pdf |title=Ontario Line Initial Business Case \u2013 July 2019|publisher=[[Metrolinx]] |accessdate=July 28, 2019 }}</ref> Another design decision Metrolinx must make is whether the elevated structure along Don Mills Road would be above or beside the road.<ref name=\"G&M-2019-07-24\"/>\n* Some of the savings for surface construction may be partially offset by the cost of building surface-to-tunnel transitions at Cherry and Gerrard streets.<ref name=\"TO-2019-10-15-A4\"/><!--\"Between Cherry Street and Gerrard Street East\"-->\n* Operating costs for the above-ground sections may be higher due to exposure to the elements.<ref name=\"TO-2019-10-15-A4\"/><!--\"Between Cherry Street and Gerrard Street East\"-->\n* Operating the Ontario Line along an elevated Lakeshore East embankment might require slower speeds in order to navigate grades and curves.<ref name=\"TO-2019-10-15-A4\"/><!--\"widening of the Lakeshore East GO rail corridor\"-->\n\n==Description==\nBased on Metrolinx's initial business case {{as of|2019|7|alt=from July 2019|df=}}, the Ontario Line route would start at its northern terminus of Science Centre station at Don Mills Road and Eglinton Avenue.<ref name=\"TheStar2019-07-22\" /> The line would proceed south along Don Mills Road on an elevated structure, passing through Flemington Park then turning west along Overlea Boulevard in Thorncliffe Park. The line would then turn to make a north\u2013south crossing of the Don Valley on a new bridge west of the existing Leaside Bridge that carries Millwood Road. On the south side of the valley, the line would enter a tunnel under Minton Place and continue underground to Cosburn station and Line 2's Pape station. The line would return to the surface just before Gerrard station, where it would follow GO Transit's [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East rail corridor]]. The Ontario Line would have a surface station, named Leslieville, where the railway right-of-way crosses Queen. The route would continue along the railway right-of-way to East Harbour station, east of the Don River, near Eastern Avenue, where there are plans to build a new GO train station. The route would cross the Don River on a bridge, descending into a tunnel under the rail corridor just east of Cherry Street. The route would turn north through Corktown station at King and Parliament streets. Between Parliament and Berkeley streets, the line would turn west under Queen Street through Moss Park station (at Sherbourne and Queen), Queen station (at Yonge) and Osgoode station (at University Avenue). The line would continue westward to a Queen/Spadina station, then southward to a King/Bathurst station. The line would turn westward again, coming to the surface just west of Strachan Avenue before arriving at Exhibition station, its southern terminus.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/07/22/ontario-line-would-run-on-just-3-kilometres-of-citys-relief-line-route-confidential-plans-show.html |title=Ontario Line would run on just 3 kilometres of city's relief line route, confidential plans show |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |first=Ben |last=Spurr |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=July 27, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"TheStar-2019-07-25\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/07/25/experts-cast-doubt-on-deadline-budget-in-ontario-line-business-case.html |title=Experts cast doubt on deadline, budget in Ontario Line business case |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |first=Ben |last=Spurr |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"G&M-2019-07-24\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/toronto/article-a-greater-potential-for-disruption-confidential-business-case-for/#comments |title='A greater potential for disruption': Confidential business case details plans for proposed Ontario Line subway project |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |first=Oliver |last=Moore |date=July 24, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Metrolinx-2019-07\"/>\n\nMetrolinx is considering a means to link Exhibition station to Ontario Place. The link could be a [[people mover]], cable cars or some other option.<ref name=\"G&M-2019-07-24\"/>\n\nThe Government of Ontario plans to use smaller train sets and a smaller gauge for the Ontario Line than those used on the Toronto subway system.<ref name=\"sun201904\" /> The City of Toronto's \"Relief Line\" proposal used [[Toronto subway rolling stock|the same conventional heavy rail subway vehicles]] as used on Lines 1, 2, and 4.<ref name=\"star-jacksonkelso\" /><ref name=\"TheStar2019-04-12a\" /> By using driverless trains with automatic train control and more frequent trains, the government expects that the line would have similar capacity to traditional heavy rail. The government also claims the alternate technology will reduce construction time and cost, as single tunnels rather than dual tunnels could be utilized.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Ontario Line's maintenance and storage facility would be located along the CP Rail corridor in the area of Wicksteed Avenue and Beth Nealson Drive. It is planned to accommodate up to 120 vehicles.<ref name=\"Metrolinx-2019-07\"/>\n\n==Stations<span id=\"Stations\"></span>==\nThe following information, largely from the Metrolinx's initial business case (IBC) report of July 2019, is subject to change.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Ontario Line stations (as of July 2019)<ref name=\"Metrolinx-2019-07\"/>\n! Station \n! style=\"width:8em\" | Type{{efn|The station type \"above ground\" used in the [[#Stations|Stations]] table means the station could be either at-grade or elevated.}} \n! style=\"width:9em\" |Neighbourhood\n! style=\"width:12em\" |Connections\n! Notes \n|-\n| {{ttcs|Science Centre}}\n| Above ground\n| [[Flemingdon Park]]\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|5}} [[Line 5 Eglinton|Eglinton]]\n| Integrated with station under construction at [[Don Mills Road]] and [[Eglinton Avenue]]\n|-\n| Flemingdon Park\n| Elevated\n| [[Flemingdon Park]]\n|\n| Near Flemingdon Park Shopping Centre\n|-\n| Thorncliffe Park \n| Elevated\n| [[Thorncliffe Park]]\n|\n| Near Overlea Boulevard and Beth Nealson Drive\n|-\n| Cosburn \n| Underground\n|[[Old East York]]\n|\n| In vicinity of Cosburn Avenue and Pape Avenue\n|-\n| {{ttcs|Pape}}\n| Underground\n|\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|2}} [[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth|Bloor\u2013Danforth]]\n| Integrated with an existing station at Pape and Danforth\n|-\n| Gerrard\n| Above ground\n| [[Riverdale, Toronto|Riverdale]]\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|506}} [[506 Carlton|Carlton]]\n| North side of [[Gerrard Street (Toronto)|Gerrard Street]] between Pape Avenue and Carlaw Avenue, along the [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East]] and [[Stouffville line|Stouffville]] [[GO Transit rail services|GO Transit rail corridors]]. Although Gerrard is the proposed site of a GO/[[SmartTrack]] station,<ref name=\"SteveMunro-2017-03-20\" /> the Metrolinx IBC made no mention of it.\n|-\n| Leslieville\n| Above ground\n| {{plainlist|\n*[[Leslieville]]\n* [[South Riverdale]]\n}}\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|501}} [[501 Queen|Queen]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|502}} [[502 Downtowner|Downtowner]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|503}} [[503 Kingston Rd|Kingston Rd]]\n| Located at the intersection of Queen Street East and GO Transit's Lakeshore East / Stouffville rail corridor\n|-\n| East Harbour \n| Above ground\n| [[Port Lands]]\n| {{rint|gotransit|rail|B}} [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East]]<br>{{rint|gotransit|rail|G}} [[Stouffville line|Stouffville]]\n| Located along GO Transit's Lakeshore East / Stouffville rail corridor between Eastern Avenue and the Don River. The station will have six tracks, with the four inner tracks for GO Transit trains and two outer tracks for the Ontario Line. Because all six tracks will be on the same level, there will be some opportunity for cross-platform transfers.<!--page 55 of IBC--> East Harbour is also a proposed station for SmartTrack service.<ref name=\"SteveMunro-2017-03-20\" /> In the vicinity of East Harbour Station, there is also a separate proposal to extend streetcar service south along Broadview Avenue into the Portlands.<ref name=\"TheStar-2019-06-24\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/04/05/sidewalk-labs-says-it-wont-pay-upfront-costs-for-new-lrt-critical-to-smart-city-waterfront-development.html |title=Sidewalk Labs says it won't pay upfront costs for new LRT critical to 'smart city' waterfront development |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |first=Ben |last=Spurr |date=June 24, 2019 |accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref> The location is the site of the proposed East Harbour office development.\n\n|-\n| Corktown \n| Underground\n| [[Corktown, Toronto|Corktown]]\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|504}} [[504 King|King]]\n| Near [[Parliament Street (Toronto)|Parliament Street]] and [[King Street (Toronto)|King Street East]]<ref name=\"TheStar2019-07-22\" />\n\n|-\n| Moss Park<ref name=\"SouthTPAPCompletion\" />\n| Underground\n| {{plainlist |\n*[[Regent Park]] \n* [[Moss Park]]\n}}\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|501}} [[501 Queen|Queen]]\n| At [[Sherbourne Street, Toronto|Sherbourne Street]] and Queen Street East\n\n|-\n| {{ttcs|Queen}} \n| Underground\n| [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University|Yonge\u2013University]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|501}} [[501 Queen|Queen]]\n| Integrated with an existing station at Queen Street and Yonge Street\n\n|-\n| {{ttcs|Osgoode}} \n| Underground\n| [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University|Yonge\u2013University]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|501}} [[501 Queen|Queen]]\n| Integrated with an existing station at Queen Street West and University Avenue\n\n|-\n| Queen/Spadina \n| Underground\n| [[Fashion District, Toronto|Fashion District]]\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|501}} [[501 Queen|Queen]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|510}} [[510 Spadina|Spadina]]\n| Near the intersection of [[Queen Street (Toronto)|Queen Street West]] and [[Spadina Avenue]]\n\n|-\n| King/Bathurst \n| Underground\n| [[Fashion District, Toronto|Fashion District]]\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|504}} [[504 King|King]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|511}} [[511 Bathurst|Bathurst]]\n| Near the intersection of [[King Street (Toronto)|King Street West]] and [[Bathurst Street (Toronto)|Bathurst Street]]\n\n|-\n| [[Exhibition GO Station|Exhibition / Ontario Place]]\n| At grade\n| [[Liberty Village]]\n| {{rint|toronto|streetcar|509|x}} [[509 Harbourfront|Harbourfront]]<br>{{rint|toronto|streetcar|511|x}} [[511 Bathurst|Bathurst]]<br>{{rint|gotransit|rail|A}} [[Lakeshore West line|Lakeshore West]]\n| North of [[Exhibition Place]], with cross-platform transfers to existing Exhibition GO Station<!--page 30 of IBC-->\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"TheStar2019-04-12a\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2019/04/12/ontario-place-advocates-wary-of-doug-fords-transit-plan.html |title=Ontario Place advocates wary of Doug Ford's transit plan |work=[[Toronto Star]] |first=David |last=Rider |date=April 12, 2019 |accessdate=April 27, 2019 |quote=Complicating the question is the fact that the exact location of the \"Ontario Place/Exhibition\" station at the line's southern terminus is, for now, as mysterious as the rail technology proposed to power it. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427235952/http