11 \u2013 F16H 49/00.\n* Sclater, Neil. (2011). \"Gears: devices, drives and mechanisms.\" ''Mechanisms and Mechanical Devices Sourcebook.'' 5th ed. New York: McGraw Hill. pp.&nbsp;131\u2013174. {{ISBN|9780071704427}}. Drawings and designs of various gearings.\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|date=May 2018}}\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://geararium.org Geararium. Museum of gears and toothed wheels] A place of antique and vintage gears, sprockets, ratchets and other gear-related objects.\n*[http://kmoddl.library.cornell.edu/index.php Kinematic Models for Design Digital Library (KMODDL)] Movies and photos of hundreds of working models at Cornell University\n*[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs12045-013-0106-3 Short Historical Account on the application of analytical geometry to the form of gear teeth]\n*[http://www.societyofrobots.com/mechanics_gears.shtml Mathematical Tutorial for Gearing (Relating to Robotics)]\n*[http://www.agma.org American Gear Manufacturers Association]\n*[http://www.geartechnology.com Gear Technology, the Journal of Gear Manufacturing]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=AyEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA120&dq=popular+science+1930&hl=en&ei=4dTRTu6lLsvUgAed8uifDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBDhG#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Wheels That Can't Slip.\"] ''Popular Science'', February 1945, pp.&nbsp;120\u2013125.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Gears}}\n{{Kinematic pair}}\n{{Portal bar|Engineering|Business|Trains}}\n\n[[Category:Gears| ]]\n[[Category:Tribology]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "2601:204:cb01:d70:f111:a263:f86c:7e1f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gear"}
{"title_page": "31 Canadian Brigade Group", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                     = 31st (Reserve) Brigade Group<br/>31 Canadian Brigade Group\n| image                         = 31 Canadian Brigade Group (logo).jpg\n| caption                       = Formation patch of the 31st Canadian Brigade Group.\n| dates                         = 1942&ndash;1946<br/>1 April 1997\u2013present\n| country                       = {{flag|Canada}}\n| branch                        = [[File:Lesser badge of the Canadian Army.svg|23px]] [[Primary Reserve]]\n| command_structure             = [[4th Canadian Division]]\n| type                          = Headquarters\n| identification_symbol_4       = \n| identification_symbol_4_label = \n| website                       = http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/31-cbg/index.page\n| ceremonial_chief              = \n| ceremonial_chief_label        = Colonel-in-Chief\n| nickname                      = \n| march                         = \n| motto                         = {{lang-la|Pro aris et focis}} (For hearth and home)<ref>{{cite web |title=31 Canadian Brigade Group |url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=980&ProjectElementID=3424 |work=Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges |publisher=Canadian Heraldic Authority |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref>\n| garrison                      = [[Wolseley Barracks]], [[London, Ontario]]\n}}\n'''31 Canadian Brigade Group''' (31 CBG; {{lang-fr|31<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}) is part of the [[4th Canadian Division]], under the [[Canadian Army]]. It encompasses the southwestern portion of [[Ontario]], and is headquartered in [[London, Ontario]]. The 31 CBG area of responsibility stretches from Hamilton to Windsor. The brigade has approximately 2,400 soldiers. Colonel Joe Robinson, CD is Commander of 31 Canadian Brigade Group. The brigade sergeant-major is Chief Warrant Officer Mark Delarosbil, CD.<ref>http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/31-cbg/index.page</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Second World War===\n31st (Reserve) Brigade Group was created, within 1 Militia District, on 1 April 1942 when the reserve force in Canada was reorganized for the war.  Like today, the formation consisted of part-time soldiers who were paraded and trained on evenings and weekends.  The brigade group was closed down on 28 November 1945 and the headquarters itself closed on 8 June 1946.<ref name=\"Domestic Military Organization 1900-1999\">{{Cite web|title=Reserve Brigades - Second World War|publisher=Canadian Soldiers.com|date=24 February 2013|url=http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/organization/reservebrigades194145.htm}}</ref>  During its existence, the brigade group was headquartered in London Ontario and it held the following organization:\n\n*Canadian Infantry Corps\n**1st (Reserve) Battalion, The Middlesex and Huron Regiment\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, Canadian Fusiliers (City of London Regiment) MG\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, The Essex Scottish Regiment\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, The Scots Fusiliers of Canada\n*Canadian Armoured Corps\n**30th (Reserve) Reconnaissance Regiment (Essex Regiment (Tank))\n*Royal Canadian Artillery\n**31st (Reserve) Field Regiment, RCA\n*Royal Canadian Engineers\n**7th/11th (Reserve) Field Company, RCE\n*Royal Canadian Army Service Corps\n**Brigade Group Company, 1st (Reserve) Divisional, RCASC\n*Royal Canadian Army Medical Corps\n**24th (Reserve) Field Ambulance, RCAMC\n*Royal Canadian Corps of Signals\n**E and J sections, No.1 (Reserve) District Signals, RCCS\n*Royal Canadian Ordnance Corps / Royal Canadian Electrical and Mechanical Engineers\n**No.2 Group,\n**No.2 (Reserve) Divisional Workshop, (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.1 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type A), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.2 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.3 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.4 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n\n===1997 to Present===\n31 Canadian Brigade Group (CBG) was recreated on 1 April 1997, with its headquarters located in London, replacing the London Militia District (LMD). Resulting from a major restructuring of the army, it was established as one of ten reserve brigade groups organized across Canada.\n\n==Brigade Composition==\n\n=== Overview ===\n31 CBG is an infantry-focused reserve brigade comprising 12 units in addition to the brigade headquarters in London. These units are spread out over southern and south-western Ontario, in London, Sarnia, Windsor, Guelph, Hamilton, St. Thomas, Waterloo, Burlington, Stratford, Owen Sound, Barrie, Cambridge, Kitchener, and Chatham. The Grey and Simcoe Foresters also provide support to the 4th Canadian Division as part of the [[Arctic Response Company Group]], supporting communities in northern Ontario and northern Canada.\n\n=== Regiments ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! 31 Canadian Brigade Group !!Branch\n! Location\n|-\n| 31 Canadian Brigade Group Headquarters ||  ||[[London, Ontario]]\n|-\n|[[1st Hussars]]|| Armoured Reconnaissance || London and [[Sarnia, Ontario|Sarnia]]\n|-\n|[[The Windsor Regiment (RCAC)]]|| Armoured Reconnaissance ||[[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor]]\n|-\n| 11th Field Artillery Regiment, RCA || Artillery ||[[Guelph]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|-\n|[[31 Combat Engineer Regiment (The Elgins)]]|| Engineer ||[[St. Thomas, Ontario|St. Thomas]] and [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]]\n|-\n| 31 Signal Regiment || Communications || Hamilton and London\n|-\n|[[The Royal Hamilton Light Infantry (Wentworth Regiment)]]|| Infantry || Hamilton and [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]]\n|-\n| 4th Battalion, [[The Royal Canadian Regiment]]|| Infantry || London and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]]\n|-\n|[[The Grey and Simcoe Foresters]]|| Infantry ||[[Owen Sound]] and [[Barrie]]\n|-\n|[[The Royal Highland Fusiliers of Canada]]|| Infantry ||[[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]] and [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]\n|-\n|[[The Essex and Kent Scottish]]|| Infantry || Windsor and [[Chatham, Ontario|Chatham]]\n|-\n|[[The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)]]|| Infantry || Hamilton\n|-\n|[[31 (London, Windsor, Hamilton) Service Battalion|31 Service Battalion]]|| Combat Service Support || Hamilton, London, and Windsor\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian Forces Land Force Command}}\n{{Canadian Forces}}\n\n[[Category:Brigades of the Canadian Army]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in London, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Canada in World War II]]\n\n\n{{Canada-mil-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=31st (Reserve) Brigade Group<br/>31 Canadian Brigade Group\n| image= 31 Canadian Brigade Group (logo).jpg\n|caption=Formation patch of the 31st Canadian Brigade Group.\n|dates= 1942&ndash;1946<br/>1997\u2013present\n|country={{flag|Canada}}\n|branch=[[File:Lesser badge of the Canadian Army.svg|23px]] [[Primary Reserve]]\n|command_structure=[[4th Canadian Division]]\n|type=Headquarters\n|identification_symbol_4=31 CBG\n|identification_symbol_4_label=Abbreviation\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|ceremonial_chief_label=Colonel-in-Chief\n|nickname=\n|march=\n|motto={{lang-la|Pro aris et focis}} (For hearth and home)<ref>{{cite web |title=31 Canadian Brigade Group |url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=980&ProjectElementID=3424 |work=Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges |publisher=Canadian Heraldic Authority |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref>\n|garrison=[[Wolseley Barracks]], [[London, Ontario]]\n}}\n'''31 Canadian Brigade Group''' (31CBG; {{lang-fr|31<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}) is part of the [[4th Canadian Division]], under the [[Canadian Army]]. It encompasses the southwestern portion of [[Ontario]], and is headquartered in [[London, Ontario]]. The 31 CBG area of responsibility stretches from Hamilton to Windsor. The brigade has approximately 2,400 soldiers. Colonel Joe Robinson, CD is Commander of 31 Canadian Brigade Group. The brigade sergeant-major is Chief Warrant Officer Mark Delarosbil, CD.<ref>http://www.army-armee.forces.gc.ca/en/31-cbg/index.page</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Second World War===\n31st (Reserve) Brigade Group was created, within 1 Militia District, on 1 April 1942 when the reserve force in Canada was reorganized for the war.  Like today, the formation consisted of part-time soldiers who were paraded and trained on evenings and weekends.  The brigade group was closed down on 28 November 1945 and the headquarters itself closed on 8 June 1946.<ref name=\"Domestic Military Organization 1900-1999\">{{Cite web|title=Reserve Brigades - Second World War|publisher=Canadian Soldiers.com|date=24 February 2013|url=http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/organization/reservebrigades194145.htm}}</ref>  During its existence, the brigade group was headquartered in London Ontario and it held the following organization:\n\n*Canadian Infantry Corps\n**1st (Reserve) Battalion, The Middlesex and Huron Regiment\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, Canadian Fusiliers (City of London Regiment) MG\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, The Essex Scottish Regiment\n**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, The Scots Fusiliers of Canada\n*Canadian Armoured Corps\n**30th (Reserve) Reconnaissance Regiment (Essex Regiment (Tank))\n*Royal Canadian Artillery\n**31st (Reserve) Field Regiment, RCA\n*Royal Canadian Engineers\n**7th/11th (Reserve) Field Company, RCE\n*Royal Canadian Army Service Corps\n**Brigade Group Company, 1st (Reserve) Divisional, RCASC\n*Royal Canadian Army Medical Corps\n**24th (Reserve) Field Ambulance, RCAMC\n*Royal Canadian Corps of Signals\n**E and J sections, No.1 (Reserve) District Signals, RCCS\n*Royal Canadian Ordnance Corps / Royal Canadian Electrical and Mechanical Engineers\n**No.2 Group,\n**No.2 (Reserve) Divisional Workshop, (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.1 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type A), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.2 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.3 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n**No.4 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), (RCOC) RCEME\n\n===1997 to Present===\n31 Canadian Brigade Group (CBG) was recreated on 1 April 1997, with its headquarters located in London, replacing the London Militia District (LMD). Resulting from a major restructuring of the army, it was established as one of ten reserve brigade groups organized across Canada.\n\n==Brigade Composition==\n\n=== Overview ===\n31 CBG is an infantry-focused reserve brigade comprising 12 units in addition to the brigade headquarters in London. These units are spread out over southern and south-western Ontario, in London, Sarnia, Windsor, Guelph, Hamilton, St. Thomas, Waterloo, Burlington, Stratford, Owen Sound, Barrie, Cambridge, Kitchener, and Chatham. The Grey and Simcoe Foresters also provide support to the 4th Canadian Division as part of the [[Arctic Response Company Group]], supporting communities in northern Ontario and northern Canada.\n\n=== Regiments ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! 31 Canadian Brigade Group !!Branch\n! Location\n|-\n| 31 Canadian Brigade Group Headquarters ||  ||[[London, Ontario]]\n|-\n|[[1st Hussars]]|| Armoured Reconnaissance || London and [[Sarnia, Ontario|Sarnia]]\n|-\n|[[The Windsor Regiment (RCAC)]]|| Armoured Reconnaissance ||[[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor]]\n|-\n| 11th Field Artillery Regiment, RCA || Artillery ||[[Guelph]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|-\n|[[31 Combat Engineer Regiment (The Elgins)]]|| Engineer ||[[St. Thomas, Ontario|St. Thomas]] and [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]]\n|-\n| 31 Signal Regiment || Communications || Hamilton and London\n|-\n|[[The Royal Hamilton Light Infantry (Wentworth Regiment)]]|| Infantry || Hamilton and [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]]\n|-\n| 4th Battalion, [[The Royal Canadian Regiment]]|| Infantry || London and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]]\n|-\n|[[The Grey and Simcoe Foresters]]|| Infantry ||[[Owen Sound]] and [[Barrie]]\n|-\n|[[The Royal Highland Fusiliers of Canada]]|| Infantry ||[[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]] and [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]\n|-\n|[[The Essex and Kent Scottish]]|| Infantry || Windsor and [[Chatham, Ontario|Chatham]]\n|-\n|[[The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders of Canada (Princess Louise's)]]|| Infantry || Hamilton\n|-\n|[[31 (London, Windsor, Hamilton) Service Battalion|31 Service Battalion]]|| Combat Service Support || Hamilton, London, and Windsor\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian Forces Land Force Command}}\n{{Canadian Forces}}\n\n[[Category:Brigades of the Canadian Army]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in London, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of Canada in World War II]]\n\n\n{{Canada-mil-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Reedeley", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/31_Canadian_Brigade_Group"}
{"title_page": "Dele Alampasu", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian professional footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Dele Alampasu\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Dele Sunday Alampasu\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1996|12|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Abuja]], Nigeria\n|height      = {{height|m=1.99}}\n|position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|currentclub = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n|clubnumber  = 12\n|youthyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n|youthclubs1 = Future Stars Academy\n|youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n|youthclubs2 = Abuja Football College\n|years1      = 2015\u20132020\n|clubs1      = [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]]\n|caps1       = 1\n|goals1      = 0\n|years2      = 2016\u20132017\n|clubs2      = \u2192 [[F.C. Cesarense|Cesarense]] (loan)\n|caps2       = 1\n|goals2      = 0\n|years3     = 2020\u2013\n|clubs3      = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n|caps3       = 0\n|goals3      = 0\n|nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132015\n|nationalteam1  = [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria U17]] \n|nationalcaps1  = 7\n|nationalgoals1 =  0\n|nationalyears2 = 2017\u2013\n|nationalteam2  = [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] \n|nationalcaps2  = 1\n|nationalgoals2 = 0\n|club-update = 04:51, 6 March 2019 (UTC)\n|ntupdate = 18:10, 19 July 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Dele Sunday Alampasu''' (born 24 December 1996) is a Nigerian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]] in the [[2020 Latvian Higher League|Latvian Higher League]], as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Club career==\nAlampasu began his career in [[Nigeria]], playing in the Lagos State Football Aasociation Future Stars Academy and for Abuja Football College. Alampasu underwent trials with [[Real Oviedo]], [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] and [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] before signing for Portuguese club [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]] in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/articles/categories/nigeria-players-abroad/dele-alampasu-speaks-out-on-his-portugal-move/200950|title=Alampasu Speaks About Portugal Move|publisher=Soccer Laduma|date=12 February 2015|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Alampasu cancelled his contract with Estoril, due to visa problems, and subsequently signed for [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/hawked-things-cannot-tell-says-alampasu|title=I have hawked things I cannot tell you, says Alampasu|publisher=The Cable|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Alampasu signed for [[F.C. Cesarense|Cesarense]] on loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4102/transfer-zone/2016/08/30/27013912/dele-alampasu-seals-cesarense-loan-move|title=Dele Alampasu seals Cesarense loan move|publisher=Goal|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> On 20 January 2019, Alampasu made his debut for Feirense in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/01/20/portugal/portuguese-liga-/rio-ave-fc/cd-feirense/2826063/|title=Rio Ave vs. Feirense 0\u20130|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Alampasu signed for Latvian club [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.today.ng/sport/football/dele-alampasu-ready-challenge-latvian-club-ventspils-280563 |title= Dele Alampasu ready for new challenge at Latvian club FK Ventspils|publisher=Today|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn 2013, Alampasu represented [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria U17]] at the [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup]], winning the Golden Glove award, as the ''Golden Eaglets'' won their fourth [[FIFA U-17 World Cup|U17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/y=2013/m=11/news=accolades-for-iheanacho-and-nigeria-2221120.html|title=Accolades for Iheanacho and Nigeria|publisher=FIFA|date=8 November 2013|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2017, Alampasu made his senior debut for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], as a 70th minute substitution, against [[Togo national football team|Togo]] in a 3\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary?gameId=479144|title=Nigeria 3\u20130 Togo|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Nigeria U17'''\n*[[FIFA U-17 World Cup]]: [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2013]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA U-17 World Cup Golden Glove]]: [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{FIFA U-17 World Cup awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alampasu, Dele}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Abuja]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Feirense players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Nigeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigeria under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigeria youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:FK Ventspils players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in Latvia]]\n\n{{Nigeria-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian professional footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Dele Alampasu\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Dele Sunday Alampasu\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1996|12|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Abuja]], Nigeria\n|height      = {{height|m=1.99}}\n|position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|currentclub = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n|clubnumber  = 12\n|youthyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n|youthclubs1 = Future Stars Academy\n|youthyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n|youthclubs2 = Abuja Football College\n|years1      = 2015\u20132020\n|clubs1      = [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]]\n|caps1       = 1\n|goals1      = 0\n|years2      = 2016\u20132017\n|clubs2      = \u2192 [[F.C. Cesarense|Cesarense]] (loan)\n|caps2       = 1\n|goals2      = 0\n|years3     = 2020\u2013\n|clubs3      = [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]\n|caps3       = 0\n|goals3      = 0\n|nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132015\n|nationalteam1  = [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria U17]] \n|nationalcaps1  = 7\n|nationalgoals1 =  0\n|nationalyears2 = 2017\u2013\n|nationalteam2  = [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] \n|nationalcaps2  = 1\n|nationalgoals2 = 0\n|club-update = 04:51, 6 March 2019 (UTC)\n|ntupdate = 18:10, 19 July 2018 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Dele Sunday Alampasu''' (born 24 December 1996) is a Nigerian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]] in the [[2020 Latvian Higher League|Latvian Higher League]], as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Club career==\nAlampasu began his career in [[Nigeria]], playing in the Future Stars Academy and for Abuja Football College. Alampasu underwent trials with [[Real Oviedo]], [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] and [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] before signing for Portuguese club [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]] in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerladuma.co.za/news/articles/categories/nigeria-players-abroad/dele-alampasu-speaks-out-on-his-portugal-move/200950|title=Alampasu Speaks About Portugal Move|publisher=Soccer Laduma|date=12 February 2015|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Alampasu cancelled his contract with Estoril, due to visa problems, and subsequently signed for [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/hawked-things-cannot-tell-says-alampasu|title=I have hawked things I cannot tell you, says Alampasu|publisher=The Cable|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Alampasu signed for [[F.C. Cesarense|Cesarense]] on loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4102/transfer-zone/2016/08/30/27013912/dele-alampasu-seals-cesarense-loan-move|title=Dele Alampasu seals Cesarense loan move|publisher=Goal|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> On 20 January 2019, Alampasu made his debut for Feirense in a 0\u20130 draw against [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2019/01/20/portugal/portuguese-liga-/rio-ave-fc/cd-feirense/2826063/|title=Rio Ave vs. Feirense 0\u20130|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Alampasu signed for Latvian club [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.today.ng/sport/football/dele-alampasu-ready-challenge-latvian-club-ventspils-280563 |title= Dele Alampasu ready for new challenge at Latvian club FK Ventspils|publisher=Today|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn 2013, Alampasu represented [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria U17]] at the [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup]], winning the Golden Glove award, as the ''Golden Eaglets'' won their fourth [[FIFA U-17 World Cup|U17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/y=2013/m=11/news=accolades-for-iheanacho-and-nigeria-2221120.html|title=Accolades for Iheanacho and Nigeria|publisher=FIFA|date=8 November 2013|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2017, Alampasu made his senior debut for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], as a 70th minute substitution, against [[Togo national football team|Togo]] in a 3\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/commentary?gameId=479144|title=Nigeria 3\u20130 Togo|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Nigeria U17'''\n*[[FIFA U-17 World Cup]]: [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2013]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA U-17 World Cup Golden Glove]]: [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2013]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{FIFA U-17 World Cup awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alampasu, Dele}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Abuja]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Feirense players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Nigeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigeria under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigeria youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:FK Ventspils players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in Latvia]]\n\n{{Nigeria-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Star O.L.A", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added Lagos State to his academy.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dele_Alampasu"}
